- In Python, a list is a built-in data type used to store an ordered collection of items.
- Lists are defined using square brackets [], with elements separated by commas.
- They are mutable, meaning their contents can be changed after creation, allowing for the addition, removal, or modification of items.
- Lists can contain elements of different data types, including integers, strings, booleans, dictionaries, or even other lists, making them heterogeneous.
- This flexibility is a key difference from arrays in languages like C or Java, where elements must be of the same type.
- append(x) -----> Adds element at the end
- insert(i, x) -----> Adds element at index i
- remove(x) -----> Removes first occurrence of element
- pop(i) -----> Removes element by index (default last
- sort() -----> Sorts list (ascending)
- reverse() -----> Reverses list
- count(x) -----> Counts occurrences of an element
- index(x) -----> Finds index of first occurrence
